<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Research Faculty Receive Eight Early Career Awards</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Barb Abney
		
		<span class="date">March 14, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 196px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1373/en_US/leicrop.jpg" height="261" width="196"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>Lei Zhai is one of three NanoScience Technology Center researchers who are exploring new ways of transporting energy for use in ever-smaller electronics devices.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004106d0153250118a9486d7201b8">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
							
								<h3>Story Images</h3>
								<ul id="story_images">
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004106d0153250118a9486d7201b8&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=0">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1373/en_US/andre.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004106d0153250118a9486d7201b8&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=1">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1373/en_US/SAIFUL.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			</ul><p  class="note">Click thumbnails for full-size images.</p>
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:babney@mail.ucf.edu">Barb Abney</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5139</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.research.ucf.edu">Office of Research and Commercialization</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>A record eight University of Central Florida researchers have received a prestigious National Science Foundation award that recognizes the nation&rsquo;s most outstanding and promising young scientists and engineers.</p>
<p>The faculty received the CAREER awards for a variety of research projects, including the development of tools for computers to automatically locate and remove threatening bugs and the study of miniature magnets and their potential for quantum computing.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We are very proud that our campus is home to so many of the nation&rsquo;s leading young scientists,&rdquo; UCF President John Hitt said. &ldquo;This award has special meaning because it represents the views of the scientific community, which recognizes what the future holds for our university. Support from the National Science Foundation will help our researchers achieve innovations in computers, energy, lasers and other technologies that benefit our region, state and nation.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Each awardee will receive a minimum of $400,000, distributed over five years.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;CAREER awards are extremely competitive,&rdquo; said M.J. Soileau, UCF&rsquo;s vice president for Research and Commercialization. &ldquo;These awards are given only after extensive review by scientific peers. To receive eight of them in these lean budget times is significant. This means that top young engineers and scientists are choosing UCF as the place to build their careers. This bodes well for the future of our university.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Three of the award recipients are from the university&rsquo;s NanoScience Technology Center. Assistant Professors <b>Lei Zhai</b>, <b>Andre Gesquiere </b>and <b>Saiful Khondaker</b> all use principles of nanoscience -- the study of materials, devices and systems on a nanometer scale -- to explore new ways of transporting energy for use in ever-smaller electronics devices.&nbsp; Gesquiere is looking at new materials that can be used to capture energy from sunlight and convert it to household use, while Zhai and Khondaker are conducting research that could one day lead to much faster and smaller computers and other electronic devices. Gesquiere and Zhai also have faculty appointments in the Department of Chemistry, and Khondaker has a faculty appointment in the Department of Physics.</p>
<p><b>Huiyang Zhou,</b> an assistant professor in the College of Engineering and Computer Science, is working on developing more efficient and effective methods of fighting computer viruses by integrating automatic bug-detection tools into computer hardware.&nbsp;</p>
<p><b>Enrique del Barco</b>, a physics professor in the College of Sciences, received an award for his research into molecular magnetic systems and how they perform in different environments. Del Barco's research into the molecular magnets may revolutionize the way we think about computers and eventually lead to &quot;quantum computers&quot; that will make the speed and processing ability of today's computers seem like dinosaurs.</p>
<p><b>Stephen Kuebler</b>, an assistant professor in the Department of Chemistry and director of the Nanophotonic Materials Group in the College of Optics and Photonics, is using lasers to create new metallic composites and studying how they interact with light. These hybrid materials could lead to new devices for sensing, high-resolution imaging, telecommunications and all-optical computing.</p>
<p><b>Nina Orlovskaya</b>, an assistant professor of Mechanical, Materials and Aerospace Engineering, is creating boron-rich hard and tough ceramic-layered materials designed to contain thermal residual stresses and withstand high critical loads under ballistic impact or other extreme conditions. The project will lead to development of tough and hard ceramic materials for use in a variety of applications.&nbsp;</p>
<p>And <b>Pawel Wocjan</b>, an assistant professor of Computer Science in the College of Engineering and Computer Science, is looking for new ways to use quantum algorithms to enhance the problem-solving capability of computers.</p>
<p>In addition to the research funding, each award includes a strong educational component, meaning UCF students and the broader community stand to benefit from the work of the recipients. Many of the projects include interaction with area middle and high school students, particularly those under-represented in science and engineering fields.</p>
<p>UCF researchers have received 28 of the early career awards since the program began in 1996.</p>
<hr />
<p><b>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</b> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 48,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
